First off, I love supporting black businesses whenever I can. Supporting involves purchasing their service and providing feedback - positive and negative.  The location and setting is nice. Ambiance easily makes you want to stay for a while. The mac and cheese was delicious as were the catfish nuggets.  On the other hand, the Bellinis left a lot to be desired. While sufficiently alcoholic, the taste was off putting, leaving an almost expired fruity taste in my mouth. At the start I asked to switch the peach preserve for a pineapple one but that didn’t help at all. I ordered the chicken and waffles. The waffles were bland and the chicken! I ate one of two pieces and barely got through the first. It wasn’t cooked properly and I could smell the “raw” on my fried thigh.  If I visit again I’ll probably stay with the seafood options.

So I had a chance to visit this establishment when it was Billy Black when the menu was southern and now was able to circle back now that they are B2 Harlem. So same space just painted and the stage removed and couches added as seating, which gave it more of a smoking lounge or den or high end ladies lounge outside the bathroom feel....... I wasn't mad at that feel. I was slightly nervous when we arrived and were the only ones there on a Thursday evening around 6ish to which my mom continuously pointed out lol (Parents!). But I was determined to see what the revamp was about so mom had to yield plus it was my birthday.  So we powered through with a great music playlist of rap, R&B and afrobeats. A decent bartender and decent apps the Mac n Cheese being the right amount of cheesy and charred in cute mini cast iron pans (presentation is everything) and the Brussels sprouts that were also the right amount of charred and garlicky. And I must say that the slightly fishy smell we detected....... nose of a bloodhound I have dude to the garbage room being behind and below our window from where we were seated. Was not evident in our pan fried salmon and black sea bass. Overall the few minutes we had the place to ourselves was heaven and once full the vibe still remained my choice was good and mom had a great time.

I went For  Brunch on Sunday with my cousin who was visiting out of town . It was my second time being there and I was excited to go again . We sat and ate. Ordered the unlimited Mimosas with our meal. Everything seemed nice including our server Andres. At some point while were sitting and talking Andres came and asked us if we could sit at the Bar because he had another couple that made reservations.... We had finished eating at that point, But found the request a little odd being that the place still had available seating... But ok I get it. We go sit at the bar and maybe 5mins later Andres brings our check, which we did not request . 3 mins later he comes to see if we were ready to pay, which we were not .  We kinda felt rushed at this point .... So fine I paid my $89.00 bill and left a $15 tip. When we asked for a refill on our unlimited Mimosas we were told that the unlimited special was for 1 1/2 hours . It didn't feel like we had been there that long , but it quickly begin to feel like we were being pushed out .  When I checked the website, I didn't read any thing about a cut off time for drinks , which is one of the main reasons people go to brunch. Our server never made us aware of this . And when is it a thing to ask a couple to move to the bar?  Overall it's a decent spot.... Good food , good drinks, but the service was horrible towards the end . That's not how you want people to feel leaving your place of business, unless you prefer for them not to return. Maybe that's what it was , maybe not .

This was an absolutely wonderful surprise. The decor and ambiance are out of a dream and I felt as if I had stepped onto a film set, perhaps the library of a very refined and well-read English Barrister (Lawyer) who might also have been an author or professor. However, once my friend and I had taken a seat at one of the restaurants "French Windows" discreetly placed above street level with very deep thickly planted window boxes outside for privacy and elegance, we realized that we were Uptown, but somehow not the Uptown I remembered from over a decade ago. The owners are incredibly friendly and the food is among the best I have had in many, many years and many, many cities. The use of the "library scene" is not only ingenious, but really works for the purpose of a restaurant. (Was there a showbiz designer involved?) I LOVED IT. Please visit it. I read a review about a girlfriend who went to the bathroom and didn't come out for an hour. You'd have to visit that bathroom to know why she stayed there. I felt the same way. Kudos and Cheers Galore to the geniuses who put this place together.

My new favorite spot in an already hopping culinary neighborhood of South Harlem.  The cocktail list is laid out well (like a periodic table) the highlight of which is pictured below. I'm writing this review because I think this place has so much potential. The decor is beautiful and it's the kind of neighborhood spot that can turn into a favorite. But food consistency is a critical component to that.

Billie's Black is a gem. The food is a 10. The decor is a 10, for a romantic evening/ 8 for kicking it with buddies. The service is FANTASTIC! I don't know what other people experienced but I have been here several times and the servers, which are predominately male (which i love because less women =less diva like tendencies), are attentive, kind, and efficient.  I just hope EVERYONE and their parents (*giggles* that was for the "New Harlem" crowd) dont get hip to it and make it impossible to dine at! LOL! Always a great, choice spot!
Love the wait staff, love the catfish strips, and love the key lime martini!!!

Nice neighborhood spot for a low-key Happy Hour or dinner.  Awesome monthly music showcase - 3rd Wednesday of the Month.  Awesome indie artists and musicians every time I go.  Rumor is the catfish is laced with something addictive - its not to be missed!!

I love this small quant restaurant.  The food is delicious, with a variety of favorite and traditional Soul-food, such as: fried whiting, catfish, chicken, salmon cakes, and grits.  However a word of advise, make sure you call 4 hours in advance for a reservation because they are always packed.

Heard of this place and the good food but slow service BUT after a great show at Harlem Stage my sisters and I were hungry snd decided on BB's. A slight hiccup w parking but the host (whose name I wished I knew) was understanding as I was the only one there but enjoying the live band, and assured us a table for 5. We were seated and Dennis, our waiter WAS THE BEST!!!! Our food was delicious and we all RAVED over the catfish strips we shared in an appy. Our black heifer and black iris martins were smooth and PERFECT in taste. We digged in each others plates sampling each others fried chicken, bbq beef ribs, stuffed catfish, mmmm-mmmm mashed potatoes,  string beans, mac/cheese and spinach - ALL SEASONED WELL AND YUMMY. We were too stuffed for desserr but was assisted by another woman w drinks and some shrimp. WE ENJOYED OUR EXPERIENCE IMMENSELY but dont take our word for it (wink)

Billie's Black is absolutely a marvel in Harlem.  The cozy, jazzy eatery features different paintings from artist around the City and the sounds are always melodious.  The Sunday Brunch has a few basic american breakfast items, but a few of my favorites are the waffles and crab cakes and the seafood omelet just to name a few. The prices are reasonable and on the moderate side - not pricey. The service is always wonderful and I just cannot get enough of Billie's Black.
I was taken here by a good friend and can't wait to go back...
Food is a bit pricey, but, I don't mind paying for grub uf its QUALITY grub I can afford...
The service is slow, but the food is delicious and you’re sure to have a good time. Try the fried catfish or the BBB Burger! The décor in the bathroom is not suitable for children.
